Subject:Re: [Jukebox-list] RE: Seeburg 1950s DiNoc Cabinet Finish
	Restorations Vol 111, no 19
As I said in an earlier post, I distinctly remember the original roll of
Di-Noc I purchased in 1981/2 to restore a Wurlitzer 1100 was a thin veneer
so if Di-Noc came in other forms later on that could be the case, but I
know that mine came in a roll and was a very thin veneer. Of course in the
Wurlitzer factory they applied it much faster on the cabinet as they were
equippped to do that but when you are doing one machine at a time in later
years it is a different animal entirely. I've owned my 1100 since 1982 and
it looks as perfect as it did 30 years ago. The cabinet itself is a
beautiful walnut veneer and the door frame, which we saw stripped down to
its bare essentials was solid steel (I think aluminum) to prevent warpage
-- not wood. All in all, It was a quality product that still holds up
today...

Ed

On Fri, Oct 19, 2012 at 5:00 PM, Mark Addleson <maddleso@gmu.edu> wrote:

> John
>
> I about three years ago, when I was restoring my Seeburg 'R', I spent a
> lot of time looking at alternative products including DiNoc, laminates,
> painting techniques, and wood veneers.  I ordered DiNoc samples of some
> possible candidates for pattern matches.
>
> If the DiNoc of the 40s/50s was essentially the same product as today's 3M
> version - the same kinds of materials - then I'm convinced (despite the
> claims on this and other lists) - that Seeburg did NOT use DiNoc on the
> 'R' but, rather, some other finish.  What was left of the original finish
> on my machine, especially on the two triangles that support the title
> strip holder, was much more like an old decal, that could scratch and
> flake off, than the thin plastic film which is today's DiNoc.
>
> One reason why I did not go for DiNoc was that the supplier, Interior
> Design Solutions, had quite a steep cutting charge on less than full rolls
> (Cameron Forte handled all my emails and questions graciously).  As I
> recall a sheet - possibly large enough to do two jukes (I was 'talking' to
> another restorer at the time) would have been well over $100 and we'd have
> needed one of each pattern.  The other reason was that none of the
> patterns I looked at (I asked for samples based on pictures of each
> pattern on the website: www.dinocfilm.com), especially the white grained
> larger side panel, was a good match.  I didn't know until I read your post
> that this was called 'bleached mahogany'.
>
> In the end I opted for precut laminates, offered at the time in a kit by
> Dick Vaught.  The patterns seem to be a fairly good match (a gloss burl
> and matt white), the surface to which they're applied is mainly flat, the
> finish is very durable, and the cost would have been roughly the same.
> I'm very happy with result.
>
> Mark
>
